Generally, it is the form of the garden, rather than the flowers, that comes to the fore at night. Perhaps this is what gives the visitor the impression that they are seeing the garden in a more authentic light, as if unfettered. In the White Garden, however, the thrusting yet indistinct spires of white veronicastrum make one understand why white or “grey” gardens (as they were first called) were also known as ghost gardens, so mysterious and sequestered they seem.
